{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569607","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569607"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:30:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:30:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22276"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22276","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22276"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.02,0.03,0.23,0.7]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15241"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108006"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15241","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15241"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22276"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90419"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"11141"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"40283"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40294"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108006","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108006"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine check-up. She was diagnosed with stage 3b chronic kidney disease (CKD) two years ago. Her medical history includes hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus. Her regular medications include perindopril, metformin, and atorvastatin. She works as a librarian and lives with her husband. She has not had any recent travel history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her estimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFR) is 38 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 (\u0026gt;90), and urine albumin-to-creatinine ratio is 45 mg/mmol (\u0026lt;3.5).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EYou note that she has not received any vaccinations in the past three years.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following vaccination schedules is most appropriate for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Influenza vaccine once only and pneumococcal vaccine every ten years","Influenza vaccine every five years and pneumococcal vaccine annually","Influenza vaccine every two years and pneumococcal vaccine every three years","Influenza vaccine annually and pneumococcal vaccine once only","Influenza vaccine annually and pneumococcal vaccine every five years"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has stage 3b chronic kidney disease (CKD) with an eGFR of 38 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2. Patients with CKD are at increased risk of infections due to immune dysfunction associated with kidney disease. Therefore, appropriate vaccination is an important preventive measure in this population.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccording to current guidelines for patients with CKD, \u003Cstrong\u003Einfluenza vaccine annually and pneumococcal vaccine every five years\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct vaccination schedule. Annual influenza vaccination is recommended for all patients with CKD due to their increased risk of complications from influenza infection. Pneumococcal vaccination is recommended every five years for patients with CKD to protect against pneumococcal disease, which can cause severe infections including pneumonia, meningitis, and bacteraemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options do not appropriately identify recommended frequency of vaccinations. Influenza vaccination should occur yearly due to rapid mutations in the influenza virus; pneumococcal vaccination is recommended every five years in CKD patients as per the CKD Management in Primary Care handbook. Patients with CKD should also receive COVID-19 vaccination and herpes zoster vaccination if age-appropriate. A comprehensive vaccination plan should be part of routine care for all patients with CKD to reduce the risk of preventable infections.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["People with chronic kidney disease (CKD) have an increased risk of infection and should receive recommended vaccinations including influenza, pneumococcal, COVID-19, and herpes zoster.","Influenza vaccination is recommended annually for patients with CKD.","Pneumococcal vaccination is recommended every five years for patients with CKD."],"references":["Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) Management in Primary Care (5th edition). Kidney Health Australia. 2024. Available from:\u00a0https://assets.kidney.org.au/resources/KHA-CKD-Handbook-5th-Ed-July2024.pdf","Australian Immunisation Handbook. Australian Government Department of Health and Aged Care. 2024. Available from: https://immunisationhandbook.health.gov.au."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90419"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22276"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90419"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-05T16:22:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-05T17:17:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15241"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108006"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"da